    <solution>
        <ul>
            <li>The domain of <m>f</m> is <m>(-\infty, \infty) = \mathbb{R}</m>.</li>
            <li>The codomain of <m>f</m> is <m>(-\infty, \infty) = \mathbb{R}</m>.</li>
            <li>The range of <m>f</m> is <m>[-1,1]</m>.</li>
            <li>The image of <m>x = \frac{\pi}{2}</m> is <m>y=1</m>.</li>
        </ul>
    </solution>

    <p>Graphing is fine when both domain and codomain are <m>\mathbb{R}</m>. If the domain is <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> and the codomain is <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>, we would need five dimensions to draw the full graph, so a geometric graph is not possible.</p>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>

  <!-- ==================== PAGE 4 ==================== -->
  <page>
    <title>Example 1: Working with a Matrix Transformation</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-1">
      <introduction>
        <p>Let
          <m>
            A=\begin{bmatrix} 1\amp 1\\[2pt] 0\amp 1\\[2pt] 1\amp 1 \end{bmatrix},\qquad
            \vec u=\begin{bmatrix} 3\\[2pt] 4 \end{bmatrix},\qquad
            \vec b=\begin{bmatrix} 7\\[2pt] 5\\[2pt] 7 \end{bmatrix}.
          </m>
        </p>
        <p>Consider the matrix transformation <m>T(\vec v)=A\vec v</m>.</p>
    </introduction>
        <task workspace="1in">
          <statement><p>Compute <m>T(\vec u)</m>.</p></statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
                Note <me>T(\vec u) = A\vec u = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} = 3\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 1\end{bmatrix} + 4\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 4 \\ 7 \end{bmatrix}</me> So, <m>T(\vec u) = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 4 \\ 7 \end{bmatrix}</m>. Another way of saying this is <m>\begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 4 \\ 7 \end{bmatrix}</m> is the image of <m>\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}</m> under <m>T</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
        </task>

        <task workspace="true">
          <statement><p>Find <m>\vec v\in\mathbb{R}^2</m> so that <m>T(\vec v)=\vec b</m>.</p></statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
                Note <me>T(\vec v) = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 5 \\ 7 \end{bmatrix} \quad \implies \quad \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}\vec v = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 5 \\ 7 \end{bmatrix}</me> We have that <me>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 7 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 5 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 7 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 7 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 5 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp 0 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 5 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</me> Therefore, <m>\vec v = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix}</m> is a vector in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> so that <m>T(\vec v) = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 5 \\ 7\end{bmatrix}</m>.
            </p>
            <p> We can check this: <me>T(\vec v) = A\vec v = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix} = 2\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 1\end{bmatrix} + 5\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 5 \\ 7 \end{bmatrix}</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
        </task>
        

        <task workspace="true">
          <statement>
            <p>Give a vector <m>\vec c\in\mathbb{R}^3</m> for which there is no <m>\vec v</m> with <m>T(\vec v)=\vec c</m>.</p>
            <p><em>Equivalently:</em> Give a <m>\vec c</m> not in the range of <m>T</m>, i.e., not in the span of the columns of <m>A</m>.</p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
                In order for there to be no <m>\vec v</m> so that <m>T(\vec v) = \vec c</m>, we need for the matrix equation <m>A\vec v = \vec c</m> to have no solution, or equivalenty, for the underlying linear system to be inconsistent. Let <m>\vec c = \begin{bmatrix} c_1 \\ c_2 \\ c_3 \end{bmatrix}</m> and note that <me>\begin{bmatrix} A \amp \rvert \amp \vec c\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp c_1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp c_2 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp c_3 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp c_1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp c_2 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp c_3 - c_1\end{bmatrix}</me> Therefore, by <xref ref="thm-inconsistent-system"/>, the system is inconsistent if and only if <m>c_3 - c_1 \neq 0</m>, or equivalently, if and only if <m>c_1 \neq c_3</m>. Thus, letting <m>\vec c = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 2\end{bmatrix}</m> will result in there being no vectors <m>\vec v \in \mathbb{R}^2</m> with <m>T(\vec v) = \vec c</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>

  <!-- ==================== PAGE 5 ==================== -->
  <page>
    <title>Linear Transformations and Superposition</title>

    <definition workspace="1in">
      <p>A function <m>T:\mathbb{R}^n\to\mathbb{R}^m</m> is <term>linear</term> if for all <m>\vec u,\vec v\in\mathbb{R}^n</m> and all scalars <m>c\in\mathbb{R}</m>:
      <ul>
        <li><m>T(\vec u+\vec v)=T(\vec u)+T(\vec v)</m>,</li>
        <li><m>T(c\,\vec v)=c\,T(\vec v)</m>.</li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    </definition>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <p workspace="1in"> By linearity, for any scalars <m>c_1,\dots,c_k</m> and vectors <m>\vec v_1,\dots,\vec v_k</m>,
    <me>
      T\!\big(c_1\vec v_1+\cdots+c_k\vec v_k\big)
      \;=\;
      c_1\,T(\vec v_1)+\cdots+c_k\,T(\vec v_k).
    </me>
    </p>

    <p workspace="0.5in">This is the <term>principle of superposition</term>. In particular, once we know <m>T(\vec e_1),\dots,T(\vec e_n)</m>, we can compute <m>T(\vec v)</m> for any <m>\vec v \in \mathbb{R}^n</m>.</p>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <fact>
      <p>Every matrix transformation <m>T_A(\vec v)=A\vec v</m> is linear.</p> 
    </fact>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>

  <!-- ==================== PAGE 6 ==================== -->
  <page>
    <title>Example 2: Geometric Actions in \m{\mathbb{R}^2}</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-2">
      <introduction>
        <p>Suppose <m>T(\vec x)=A\vec x</m>. Give a brief geometric description of the action of <m>T</m> in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> for each matrix.</p>
      </introduction>
        <task workspace="true">
            <statement>
          <p><m>A=\begin{bmatrix} 0\amp 1\\[2pt] 1\amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    First, we can see what <m>T</m> does to specific vectors. Note that <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} = 1\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} + 0\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</me>. Graphing the input vector <m>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m> and the output vector <m>\begin{bmatrix}0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m> and comparing, we see that the linear transformation <m>T</m> might have rotated the vector <m>90^\circ</m> counterclockwise OR it may have reflected the vector about the line <m>y = x</m> (this swaps the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> entries) OR it may have done something else. Let's try another vector and see if it narrows down the possibilities. Note that <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} = 0\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} + 1\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</me>. Again, graphing the input and output vectors and comparing, we see that rotation by <m>90^\circ</m> counterclockwise is no longer a valid option. It does still seem that reflection about the line <m>x = x</m> is possible. Let's now see how the linear transformation changes an arbitrary input. Note that <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = x\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} + y\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} y \\ x \end{bmatrix}</me>. Therefore, we see that <m>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} y \\ x \end{bmatrix}</m> for any input vector <m>\vec x = \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}</m>. Thus, the linear transformation <m>T</m> reflects vectors about the line <m>y = x</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task workspace="true">
            <statement>
          <p><m>A=\begin{bmatrix} 1\amp 0\\[2pt] 0\amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Again, we can start to get an idea of how this transformation affects vectors geometrically by seeing how it acts on particular vectors. Note that <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} = 1\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + 0\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</me>. So, <m>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m> which makes it look like <m>T</m> doesn't do anything. Let's try another input vector: <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} = 0\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + 1\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</me>. This time, <m>T</m> sent our input vector to the origin. Maybe you can see what kind of geometric operation can act on the previous two vectors in such a way. If not, let's see what <m>T</m> does to an arbitrary vector. Note that <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = x\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + y\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} x \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</me>. Now, we see that <m>T</m> is projecting vectors onto the <m>x</m>-axis. (If you don't know what projection is, we will discuss it Chapter 6.)                    
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task workspace="true">
          <statement>
            <p><m>A=\begin{bmatrix} k\amp 0\\[2pt] 0\amp k \end{bmatrix}</m> for <m>k\in\mathbb{R}</m></p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
                Let's go ahead and see what <m>T</m> does to an arbitrary vector: <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} k \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp k \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = x\begin{bmatrix} k \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + y\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ k \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} xk \\ yk \end{bmatrix} = k\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}</me>. Therefore, <m>T</m> simply multiplies the input vector by <m>k</m>. Geometrically, this results in the input vector being scaled by <m>|k|</m> and rotated by <m>180^\circ</m> if <m>k &lt; 0</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>

  <!-- ==================== PAGE 7 ==================== -->
  <page>
    <title>Example 3: Geometric Actions in \m{\mathbb{R}^3}</title>
    <example xml:id="ex-3">
      <introduction><p>Describe the effect of <m>T_A</m> on vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>.</p></introduction>
        <task workspace="true">
          <statement>
            <p><m>A=\begin{bmatrix} 1\amp 0\amp 0\\[2pt] 0\amp 1\amp 0\\[2pt] 0\amp 0\amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
                Feel free to start by seeing what <m>T</m> does to particular inputs. We will go ahead and see how <m>T</m> acts on an arbitrary vector. Note that <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1\amp  0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{bmatrix} = x\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + y\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + z\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</me>. Note that <m>T</m> sets the <m>z</m>-compenent of any input vector to <m>0</m>. Geometrically, this result in the input vector getting projected onto the <m>xy</m>-plane.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task workspace="true">
            <statement>
          <p><m>A=\begin{bmatrix} 1\amp 0\amp 0\\[2pt] 0\amp -1\amp 0\\[2pt] 0\amp 0\amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Note that <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1 \amp  0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{bmatrix} = x\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + y\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ -1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + z\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} x \\ -y \\ z \end{bmatrix}</me>. Note that <m>T</m> negates the <m>y</m>-compenent of any input vector. Geometrically, this result in the input vector getting reflected about the <m>xz</m>-plane.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>

  <!-- ==================== PAGE 8 ==================== -->
  <page>
    <title>Example 4: Building the Matrix from Basis Images</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-4">
      <statement>
        <p>A linear transformation <m>T:\mathbb{R}^2\to\mathbb{R}^3</m> satisfies</p>
        <me>
          T\!\left(\begin{bmatrix}1\\[2pt]0\end{bmatrix}\right)
          =
          \begin{bmatrix}5\\[2pt]-7\\[2pt]2\end{bmatrix},
          \qquad
          T\!\left(\begin{bmatrix}0\\[2pt]1\end{bmatrix}\right)
          =
          \begin{bmatrix}-3\\[2pt]8\\[2pt]0\end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
        <p>What is the matrix that represents <m>T</m>?</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
            We want to find <m>A</m> so that <m>T(\vec x) = A\vec x </m>. Let's use the given data points and the fact the <m>T</m> is a linear transformation to determine how <m>T</m> acts on an arbitrary vector. First, note that we can represent an arbitrary vector <m>\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}</m> as a linear combination of <m>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m> in the following way. <me>\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = x\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + y\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</me>. Applying the linear transformation <m>T</m> to both sides yields <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}\right) = T\left(x\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + y\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}\right)</me>. Since <m>T</m> is a linear transfomration, we know that <m>T(\vec u + \vec v) = T(\vec u) + T(\vec v)</m>. Therefore, we have that <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}\right) = T\left(x\begin{bmatrix}1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}\right) + T\left(y\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}\right)</me> Another property of linear transformations we can use is that <m>T(c\vec v) = cT(\vec v)</m>. Thus, we have that <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}\right) = x \ T\left(\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}\right) + y \ T\left(\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}\right)</me>. Subbing in the given information, we have that <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}\right) = x\begin{bmatrix} 5 \\ -7 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix} + y\begin{bmatrix} -3 \\ 8 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp -3 \\ -7 \amp 8 \\ 2 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}</me>. Therefore, we have that <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp -3 \\ -7 \amp 8 \\ 2 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m> is the matrix that represents <m>T</m>.</p>
            <p>
                Note: The matrix representing a linear transformation is usually not formed by simply putting the given vectors as the columns. It was in this example since we were told what <m>T</m> did to the <term>standard vectors</term>. We will learn more about standard vectors and the matrix of a linear transformation in the next section.
            </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </page>

</handout>